<subSubSection lastPageId="6" lastPageNumber="128" pageId="5" pageNumber="127" type="discussion">
<paragraph blockId="5.[151,1437,1406,2011]" lastBlockId="6.[151,1436,151,287]" lastPageId="6" lastPageNumber="128" pageId="5" pageNumber="127">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,308,1910,1935]" pageId="5" pageNumber="127">Remarks</emphasis>
. The new species is somewhat similar to 
<taxonomicName authority="Cherian" authorityName="Cherian" box="[779,1025,1910,1935]" class="Insecta" family="Chloropidae" genus="Apotropina" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="5" pageNumber="127" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="tomentosa">
<emphasis box="[779,926,1911,1934]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="127">A. tomentosa</emphasis>
Cherian
</taxonomicName>
, but can be separated from the latter by the following features: proboscis bright brown to yellow; mid tibia brown with yellow basally; hind tibia with a short black apical spur; R 
<number box="[436,444,1997,2011]" pageId="5" pageNumber="127" value="4.0">4</number>
+ 
<number box="[453,460,1997,2011]" pageId="5" pageNumber="127" value="5.0">5</number>
and M 
<number box="[539,544,1997,2011]" pageId="5" pageNumber="127" value="1.0">1</number>
+ 
<number box="[554,563,1997,2011]" pageId="5" pageNumber="127" value="2.0">2</number>
convergent distally. In 
<taxonomicName box="[825,971,1983,2006]" class="Insecta" family="Chloropidae" genus="Apotropina" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="5" pageNumber="127" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="tomentosa">
<emphasis box="[825,971,1983,2006]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="127">A. tomentosa</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, the proboscis is brownish black; the mid tibia is yellowish except for brown at middle; the hind tibia lacks a short black apical spur; the R 
<number box="[1266,1274,166,180]" pageId="6" pageNumber="128" value="4.0">4</number>
+ 
<number box="[1282,1289,166,180]" pageId="6" pageNumber="128" value="5.0">5</number>
and M 
<number box="[1369,1374,166,180]" pageId="6" pageNumber="128" value="1.0">1</number>
+ 
<number box="[1384,1393,166,180]" pageId="6" pageNumber="128" value="2.0">2</number>
are divergent distally (
<bibRefCitation author="Cherian" box="[360,518,190,215]" pageId="6" pageNumber="128" refString="Cherian, P. T. (2002) The fauna of India and the adjacent countries-Diptera. volume IX Chloropidae (part 1) Siphonellopsinae and Rhodesiellinae. Zoological Survey of India, Kolkata, pp. 1 - 368." type="journal article" year="2002">
Cherian 
<number box="[457,518,191,215]" pageId="6" pageNumber="128" value="2002.0">2002</number>
</bibRefCitation>
).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="6" pageNumber="128" type="etymology">
<paragraph blockId="6.[151,1436,151,287]" pageId="6" pageNumber="128">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,326,226,251]" pageId="6" pageNumber="128">Etymology</emphasis>
. The specific name is from the Latin 
<emphasis box="[756,823,227,251]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="128">longi-</emphasis>
(“long”) and 
<emphasis box="[981,1090,227,250]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="128">processus</emphasis>
(“processus”), referring to the postgonite with a long process on inner distal end.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
